In the Work Cycle, you'll do the same with whatever fits: full-time, real-world work, for the span of the cycle. By dedicating a cycle to a job, you give yourself permission to treat that employment as your core learning experience (rather than something you're squeezing in on weekends). You'll gain so much more by treating work as a learning laboratory: you're not just earning money (though that's nice), you're observing how a business operates, picking up skills on the job, and proving to yourself that you can thrive on the job. Even good jobs have parts that suck, but you've got to learn to thrive in any environment — you learn to show up on time, adapt to workplace dynamics, and take pride in doing even “menial” tasks well. The Work Cycle is also a reality check that keeps you grounded. It connects all those other crazy adventures back to practical life — you see how your new skills can make you stand out on a team. And if the job you take happens to align with a passion, it might even turn into a career path or at least a valuable network. By the end of this cycle, you'll have real job experience on your résumé while your college peers might still have nothing but term papers and debt. You'll understand the Li value of a dollar earned, and you'll return to the next cycle with sharper discipline and a healthier > bank account.
